item.title: U.K. Economy Shrinks by More Than Any Other Rich Country
item.description: The U.K. recorded a steeper second-quarter contraction than its peers, a performance that means it suffered the worst economic hit from coronavirus in Europe as well as reporting the highest death toll.

item.title: Watchdog Concludes Arms Sales to Gulf States Complied With U.S. Law
item.description: The State Department’s office of the inspector general has concluded that an emergency declaration facilitating $8 billion in weapons sales to U.S. allies in the Gulf last year complied with the law.

item.title: Ex-Mexican President Enrique Peña Nieto Accused of Corruption by Former State-Oil Chief
item.description: The former head of Mexico’s state-oil company accused former president Enrique Peña Nieto and his former finance minister of instructing him to funnel bribes to the 2012 presidential campaign, the country’s Attorney General said.

item.title: Russia Registers World's First Covid-19 Vaccine Despite Safety Concerns
item.description: Some health and pharmaceutical officials in Russia and the West have expressed alarm at the speed with which scientists have developed a vaccine, worrying that the Kremlin is sacrificing the health of the country’s citizens for the sake of prestige.

item.title: Lebanon Seeks to Fill Power Vacuum Amid Worst Crisis in Decades
item.description: The country’s leaders shifted their focus to forming a new government, a day after the cabinet resigned under pressure from protesters furious about last week’s deadly explosion.

item.title: Cruise Ship Owners Left Thousands of Workers Adrift for Months
item.description: With cruise ship passengers gone and Covid-19 lurking, crew members remained stuck on vessels waiting to get home. “We were in danger and were told nothing,” said one employee.
